<!DOCTYPE html><html><head><meta charset="UTF-8"></head><body><div style="padding: 20px; font-family: Calibri, sans-serif; line-height: 1.6;"><div style="font-family: Arial, sans-serif; padding: 20px;"><h1 style="text-align: center; color: #1f2937; font-weight: normal;">Environment</h1><div style="display: flex; justify-content: space-between; margin-bottom: 20px;"><p><strong>Date of Preparation:</strong> 2025-11-19</p><p><strong>Date of Teaching:</strong> N/A</p></div><h2 style="color: #2563eb;">Unit 1. Environmental Awareness</h2><h3 style="color: #4b5563;">1</h3><h3 style="color: #dc2626; margin-top: 20px;">A. Objectives:</h3><p><strong>1. Identify Environmental Problems (Knowledge):</strong> Students will be able to identify and describe at least three major environmental problems, understanding their basic causes and effects.</p><p><strong>2. Discuss Environmental Issues (Skill):</strong> Students will be able to discuss environmental issues using appropriate vocabulary and grammar, expressing personal opinions and proposing potential solutions.</p><p><strong>3. Value Environmental Protection (Attitude):</strong> Students will appreciate the importance of environmental protection and feel a sense of personal responsibility towards adopting sustainable living practices.</p><h3 style="color: #dc2626; margin-top: 20px;">B. Competences:</h3><p><strong>1. Language focus:</strong></p><ul style="list-style-position: inside; padding-left: 10px;"><li><strong>Environmental Vocabulary:</strong> Vocabulary related to environmental issues and solutions: pollution, deforestation, climate change, global warming, renewable energy, recycling, sustainability, conservation, carbon footprint, ecosystem, endangered species, greenhouse gases.</li><li><strong>Cause and Effect Structures:</strong> Expressing cause and effect using conjunctions and phrases: 'because of,' 'due to,' 'as a result,' 'consequently,' 'leads to,' 'if...then...'. (e.g., 'If we continue deforestation, then many species will lose their habitats.')</li><li><strong>Expressing Opinions and Suggestions:</strong> Functional language for expressing opinions, agreeing/disagreeing, and making suggestions: 'In my opinion...', 'I believe that...', 'I agree/disagree because...', 'What if we...?', 'We should/could...', 'It's important to...'.</li></ul><p><strong>2. Skills:</strong></p><ul style="list-style-position: inside; padding-left: 10px;"><li><strong>Speaking:</strong> Engaging in discussions about environmental issues, expressing personal opinions, offering suggestions, and articulating reasons for their perspectives clearly and coherently.</li><li><strong>Listening:</strong> Understanding spoken information and discussions related to environmental topics, identifying main ideas and specific details.</li><li><strong>Reading Comprehension:</strong> Comprehending short texts, infographics, or statements about environmental problems and solutions.</li><li><strong>Critical Thinking &amp; Problem Solving:</strong> Analyzing complex environmental problems, evaluating different perspectives, and synthesizing information to propose viable solutions.</li></ul><p><strong>3. Attitudes:</strong></p><ul style="list-style-position: inside; padding-left: 10px;"><li>Developing a deeper understanding and consciousness of environmental challenges facing the planet and local communities.</li><li>Fostering a sense of personal and collective responsibility for environmental protection and sustainable living.</li><li>Cultivating empathy towards the natural environment, its inhabitants, and future generations affected by environmental degradation.</li></ul><h3 style="color: #dc2626; margin-top: 20px;">C. Preparations:</h3><p>- <strong>Visual Aids for Warm-up:</strong> Print diverse pictures depicting various environmental problems (e.g., air pollution, plastic waste, deforestation, melting glaciers, endangered animals) for the warm-up activity.</p><p>- <strong>Vocabulary Handouts:</strong> Prepare handouts with environmental vocabulary terms and their definitions/pictures for a matching activity. Ensure there are enough copies for each student or pair.</p><p>- <strong>Group Activity Materials:</strong> Have large sheets of paper or poster boards and markers ready for group brainstorming and categorization activities.</p><p>- <strong>Classroom Setup &amp; Tools:</strong> Ensure access to a whiteboard or projector to write down key vocabulary, grammar points, and discussion questions. A timer is useful for managing activity durations.</p><h3 style="color: #dc2626; margin-top: 20px;">D. Methods:</h3><p>- Communicative Language Teaching (CLT)</p><h3 style="color: #dc2626; margin-top: 20px;">E. Procedures:</h3><table style="width: 100%; border-collapse: collapse; margin-top: 10px;"><thead><tr style="background-color: #fef08a;">
                <th style="border: 1px solid #000; padding: 8px;">Time/Stages</th>
                <th style="border: 1px solid #000; padding: 8px;">Activities</th>
                <th style="border: 1px solid #000; padding: 8px;">Interactions</th>
            </tr></thead><tbody><tr><td style="border: 1px solid #000; padding: 8px; vertical-align: top;" rowspan="2">
                            <b>Warm-up &amp; Introduction</b><br>7 minutes
                        </td><td style="border: 1px solid #000; padding: 8px; vertical-align: top;">Display pictures of various environmental problems (e.g., smog, plastic waste, deforestation, melting glaciers). Ask students: "What do you see?" "What problems do these pictures show?" Elicit initial vocabulary and ideas from the students.</td><td style="border: 1px solid #000; padding: 8px; vertical-align: top; text-align: center;">T-S, S-S</td></tr><tr><td style="border: 1px solid #000; padding: 8px; vertical-align: top;">Briefly introduce the lesson topic: "Environment." State the learning objectives for the lesson and give a brief overview of the activities planned.</td><td style="border: 1px solid #000; padding: 8px; vertical-align: top; text-align: center;">T-S</td></tr><tr><td style="border: 1px solid #000; padding: 8px; vertical-align: top;" rowspan="2">
                            <b>Vocabulary &amp; Concept Building</b><br>15 minutes
                        </td><td style="border: 1px solid #000; padding: 8px; vertical-align: top;">Provide students with a handout containing a list of environmental terms (e.g., pollution, deforestation, climate change, recycling, renewable energy, sustainability) and their corresponding definitions or illustrative images. Students individually match the terms with their definitions/images. Afterward, they work in pairs to check their answers and discuss any unfamiliar vocabulary.</td><td style="border: 1px solid #000; padding: 8px; vertical-align: top; text-align: center;">Individual, S-S</td></tr><tr><td style="border: 1px solid #000; padding: 8px; vertical-align: top;">Divide students into small groups (3-4 students). Give each group a large sheet of paper. Ask them to categorize environmental problems (e.g., Air Pollution, Water Pollution, Land Pollution, Climate Change, Biodiversity Loss) and brainstorm specific examples or related concepts for each category. Groups then briefly share one or two points with the class.</td><td style="border: 1px solid #000; padding: 8px; vertical-align: top; text-align: center;">Group Work, S-S</td></tr><tr><td style="border: 1px solid #000; padding: 8px; vertical-align: top;" rowspan="2">
                            <b>Discussion &amp; Solution-Oriented Thinking</b><br>15 minutes
                        </td><td style="border: 1px solid #000; padding: 8px; vertical-align: top;">Prompt students to individually think about one environmental problem they are most concerned about and why. They should consider its causes and potential effects. Then, students pair up and share their thoughts with their partner, elaborating on their concerns and initial ideas for solutions.</td><td style="border: 1px solid #000; padding: 8px; vertical-align: top; text-align: center;">Individual, S-S</td></tr><tr><td style="border: 1px solid #000; padding: 8px; vertical-align: top;">Each group from Activity 2.2 is assigned (or chooses) one specific environmental problem to focus on. They must discuss and brainstorm possible solutions, distinguishing between individual actions and larger-scale governmental/global initiatives. Each group then briefly presents their chosen problem and proposed solutions to the class. The teacher facilitates a brief Q&amp;A and class discussion after each presentation.</td><td style="border: 1px solid #000; padding: 8px; vertical-align: top; text-align: center;">Group Work, S-S, T-S</td></tr><tr><td style="border: 1px solid #000; padding: 8px; vertical-align: top;" rowspan="2">
                            <b>Wrap-up &amp; Reflection</b><br>8 minutes
                        </td><td style="border: 1px solid #000; padding: 8px; vertical-align: top;">Ask students to individually reflect on the lesson and write down one personal action or 'pledge' they can commit to taking to contribute to environmental protection (e.g., 'I will reduce my plastic use,' 'I will save water'). Students can share their pledge with the class or a partner if time allows.</td><td style="border: 1px solid #000; padding: 8px; vertical-align: top; text-align: center;">Individual, T-S</td></tr><tr><td style="border: 1px solid #000; padding: 8px; vertical-align: top;">The teacher recaps the key vocabulary, concepts, and discussion points from the lesson. Assign homework: Students are to research a local environmental initiative or a specific species affected by an environmental problem and be prepared to discuss their findings in the next class.</td><td style="border: 1px solid #000; padding: 8px; vertical-align: top; text-align: center;">T-S</td></tr></tbody></table></div></div></body></html>